Text.Value: But you're not from Elturel, either. I can tell.
Fine. Take it as a grudging payment for the rescue. Now leave me in peace.
You almost seem honest.
It was worth a shot.
Here. Now go back to the pit that made you.
I think not. Go and strip the bugbear for parts if you're that desperate.
That bloody erinyes. Devils just can't stand to lose.
I can put this to really good use. Thank you.
COIN. OR. DEATH.
Bad liar, but good killer. The coin - now.
Now take my regards back to that pouting erinyes and leave me alone.
... that's a fair trade. Here. Take this soul back to the damned place it came from.
A soul coin, eh? Whoever it belongs to won't let it go easily. You ready for that?
Let me guess: your devil mistress sent you to get her soul coin back. Too bad. I earned it fair and square.
But if you're not here for the coin, I'd rather enjoy the quiet. There's not much of it anywhere else.
It's a soul, wrapped up in a terrible iron package. Don't ask whose, because I don't know.
You got what you came for. Just go somewhere else.
Gods, I hope not. I left home at sixteen for a reason.
And I thought I was doomed. Now I feel sorry for you.
So, thank you. Not a lot of people watching my back these days.
Considering you turned that bugbear into paste...
Look, I appreciate you killing the bugbear, but this coin is all I have. So thank you, but leave me alone.
Considering what I've seen? You'd be surprised.
Then our interests barely intersect.
That coin's worth plenty. Don't let a squid get their tentacles on it.
Coin? Mistress? You lost me.
No, I don't. But that coin of yours is mine.
My 'devil mistress' can go fuck herself. I don't serve Zariel - or anyone.
That bugbear would have crushed your skull. This is the thanks I get?
I'm Karlach. If you've spent any time in Avernus, you might've heard of me.
Why thank you, dread slayer of bugbears. You shall live forever in my memory.
COIN OR DEATH. NOW.
The coin, now. Or you can be alone in your grave.
From hellspawn to angry druids... I'm definitely buying my way to Baldur's Gate.
What's that saying? Honesty late is honesty halved?
Your mother and I have a lot in common.
A mind flayer abducted me, and its ship went straight to Avernus.
And now I've misplaced the cursed thing! You know what? Good riddance.
My gods. Of course. Zariel's prize soldier. You must know what it's like trying to evade a devil better than anyone.
A new life. Imagine.
Well, that's quite the story.
The fact that you haven't made a play for it yourself is... interesting. Who are you?
So I'll call us even. Let me go back to relaxing away from all the noise down below.
You got me. Hand the coin over and I'll be on my way.
Are we done?
I've been to Avernus, but I'm no devil's servant.
I promise I'm not working for that devil.
And I... I don't even have the coin anymore. Beshaba take me, just bugger off.
Yes. No. Argh. Bloody thing's been almost more trouble than it's worth - and it's worth a lot.
Worthy of a coin, I think, except... someone seems to have picked my pocket. Gods damn it all.
How about this? You give me the coin. Now.
Would have been breathing my last if your friend hadn't killed that bugbear.
I'm sure there are other bugbears to kill. Best of luck finding them.
Oh man, a soul coin? Wouldn't mind getting my hands on that...

EditorData.NodeContext: Very interested but maybe downplaying her interest.

Text.Value: Here. Take this. It's worth a fortune. But a fortune's not worth much if you're dead. Consider it payment for saving my life.
You have good timing. Never been much of a fighter, so wrestling a bugbear would have gone poorly.
So thanks for the rescue, but you're welcome to the bugbear's spoils, not mine.
How in the hells could you know about that?
Leave.
Leave.
What exactly is this coin?
But you're not here for heroics, are you? Avernus' stench is all over your skin.
*A soul coin, true to its name, holds a mortal soul inside. It serves in the Nine Hells as very valuable currency.*
You wouldn't believe me if I told you.
You might be hell-sent, but you're a bad liar.
Sure. And my father's the Dark Prince!
I talked an erinyes out of her favourite soul coin without blinking. And you're not half as scary as she was.
Yet I'd clock you as one of her bruisers a mile off. You want me to believe you reek of Avernus by, what, coincidence?
...that's a good trade. Except the coin seems to have slipped through a hole in my pocket somewhere. Damn it.
Since you did... kill him. And I appreciate that part. So thanks.
Care to explain why you reek of the Hells?
No. Coin. Now.
The Blade of Frontiers cavorting with devils? Don't be absurd.
The path I follow is far more noble - if you possess a devil's artefact, you should leave it in my charge.
Quite the title. Means absolutely nothing to me.
I'm glad someone can. Better in your hands than a devil's.
You hand the coin over, or I kill you. How about that?
I ran away from Zariel's service the first chance I got. I'm making a new life now.
I hope it brings you better luck than it has me.
My mother's a warlock. Taught me when a fiend's tongue is twisting.
Deadly. Wait 'til you see what I can do with that thing.

EditorData.NodeContext: Happy the player got their hands on a soul coin, which she can use to supercharge her engine.

Text.Value: I'm going to be chased all over Faern for this damn coin, aren't I?

Synopsis: Nadira is a witty tiefling that survived Avernus and escaped with a soul coin, a valuable currency of the Hells. She suspects the player works for the original owner of the coin, a devilish erinyes, and will have to be persuaded in order to hand it over.
